The paper deals with the application of deep learning methods to detect user confusion in eye-tracking data. This involves analyzing both the temporal and visuospatial aspects of the data. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). The use of CNNs suggests that cs.CV (Computer Vision) is also a likely sub-category. The use of RNNs suggests that cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another possible sub-category. The paper also involves natural language processing to some extent, which suggests cs.CL (Computation and Language) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the use of deep learning methods in general suggests cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as a possible sub-category.
